Thomas Hooker, Hartford Connecticut, 1586-1908' over many years; his eyesight failed before the work was complete. The 1909 volume is the foundational primary source for this entire project — the work that made every later genealogy of the Hooker line possible.","number":1},{"number":2,"category":"military","header":"Wounded three times, twice promoted for gallantry","body":"He entered Navy service 1861 as acting master (volunteer); was the first acting master wounded in the Civil War; wounded twice more during the conflict; was twice promoted for gallantry. Transferred to regular Navy; retired Commander December 1884."},{"number":3,"category":"career","header":"Commanded a ship at twenty-three","body":"He took his first ship command at twenty-three — well before his Civil War volunteer service. The early experience prepared him for the 1861 enlistment as acting master in the U.S. Navy when Lincoln's volunteer force was first called."},{"number":4,"category":"lineage","header":"Nephew of Declaration signer Roger Sherman","body":"His mother Elisabeth Daggett was a niece of Roger Sherman of Connecticut — signer of both the Declaration of Independence and the U.S. Constitution. The 1903 Brooklyn Eagle obituary erroneously called Sherman 'Robert' rather than Roger — a common period misprint."}],"cross_connections":[{"type":"family_connection","related_id":"T01819","display_label":"Talcott compiled the parallel 1876 Talcott Genealogy book","link_text":"Brig. Gen. Sebastian Visscher Talcott"},{"type":"parallel_careers","related_id":"X02790","display_label":"Compiled 1909 Hooker parallel to Whittlesey Memorials co-author","link_text":"Charles Barnes Whittlesey"},{"type":"parallel_careers","related_id":"HD3790","display_label":"Compiled 1909 Hooker parallel to Whittlesey's 1855 history","link_text":"Col. Henry Martyn Whittlesey"},{"related_id":"X02819","display_label":"Great-uncle: Declaration of Independence and U.S. Constitution signer","type":"family_connection","link_te